774
00:44:11,157 --> 00:44:12,831
<i>to make normal conversation</i>
<i>feasible.</i>

775
00:44:12,867 --> 00:44:14,421
<i>This is Capricorn Control.</i>

776
00:44:14,458 --> 00:44:18,128
Capricorn One, this is Houston.
Capricorn One, this is Houston.

777
00:44:18,165 --> 00:44:20,168
<i>Roger, Houston,</i>
<i>this is Capricorn One.</i>

778
00:44:20,506 --> 00:44:22,279
<i>Houston, do you have a picture?</i>

779
00:44:22,315 --> 00:44:24,015
Roger, Capricorn, we have a picture.

780
00:44:24,051 --> 00:44:27,006
We have three anxious ladies here
who would like to talk to you.

781
00:44:27,347 --> 00:44:28,461
<i>Roger, Houston.</i>

782
00:44:28,890 --> 00:44:30,598
<i>We'd sure like to talk to them.</i>

783
00:44:30,725 --> 00:44:33,119
Okay, go ahead, but keep it short.

784
00:44:33,155 --> 00:44:35,512
Remember, this is long distance.

785
00:44:36,315 --> 00:44:37,180
Jack?

786
00:44:38,651 --> 00:44:39,949
Jack, it's Betty.

787
00:44:39,986 --> 00:44:42,856
<i>- Hey, Betty, how are you?</i>
- You look fine.

788
00:44:43,114 --> 00:44:47,159
<i>Thanks. You know we can't see you</i>
<i>up here, but you sure sound terrific.</i>

789
00:44:47,410 --> 00:44:50,162
I miss you. So do the kids.

790
00:44:51,915 --> 00:44:54,323
<i>Okay, I miss them too,</i>
<i>more than you all know.</i>

791
00:44:55,503 --> 00:44:56,333
Peter?

792
00:44:57,630 --> 00:44:58,495
It's Sharon.

793
00:44:58,839 --> 00:45:00,464
<i>I told you never to call me here.</i>

794
00:45:00,925 --> 00:45:02,004
Are you feeling well?

795
00:45:02,510 --> 00:45:03,708
<i>I'm feeling very well.</i>

796
00:45:04,220 --> 00:45:05,465
<i>How's Sandy?</i>

797
00:45:05,889 --> 00:45:08,767
Well, she's got the part of Wendy
in her school play.

798
00:45:08,804 --> 00:45:10,239
They're doing Peter Pan.

799
00:45:10,276 --> 00:45:11,675
<i>That's terrific.</i>

800
00:45:12,479 --> 00:45:13,855
You sound so close.

801
00:45:14,315 --> 00:45:17,435
It's hard to believe you really are
that far away in space.

802
00:45:17,693 --> 00:45:19,271
<i>It's hard for me to believe it, too.</i>

803
00:45:20,780 --> 00:45:21,646
Bru?

804
00:45:21,740 --> 00:45:22,771
<i>Hello, Kay.</i>

805
00:45:23,158 --> 00:45:24,652
We're all so proud of you.

806
00:45:25,994 --> 00:45:27,275
Can you hear me, Bru?

807
00:45:28,497 --> 00:45:29,327
<i>Yes.</i>

808
00:45:31,584 --> 00:45:33,991
- I'm not sure of Brubaker.
- Keep watching.

809
00:45:34,337 --> 00:45:37,006
Bru? I have a surprise for you.

810
00:45:37,256 --> 00:45:38,087
<i>What?</i>

811
00:45:39,300 --> 00:45:42,586
I said I have a surprise for you.

812
00:45:43,180 --> 00:45:44,129
<i>What is it?</i>

813
00:45:44,431 --> 00:45:48,346
Charles wrote a composition in school
and he won an award.

814
00:45:49,061 --> 00:45:50,306
May I read it to you?

815
00:45:53,024 --> 00:45:54,483
Bru, can you hear me?

816
00:45:54,901 --> 00:45:55,980
<i>Yes...</i>

817
00:45:57,946 --> 00:45:59,109
<i>please, read it to me.</i>

818
00:45:59,406 --> 00:46:01,482
It doesn't look good.
Do I cut the transmission?

819
00:46:01,658 --> 00:46:03,117
Not until I tell you.

820
00:46:03,452 --> 00:46:07,497
'My father, by Charles Brubaker, Jr.'

821
00:46:09,500 --> 00:46:11,991
'My father is far away from me now.

822
00:46:13,087 --> 00:46:14,463
He is flying to Mars.

823
00:46:15,006 --> 00:46:16,666
<i>I miss him very much.</i>

824
00:46:17,342 --> 00:46:19,465
<i>I always miss him when</i>
<i>he goes away.</i>

825
00:46:20,512 --> 00:46:22,090
<i>I'm not sad, though.</i>

826
00:46:22,723 --> 00:46:24,881
<i>I used to be sad when</i>
<i>he went away.</i>

827
00:46:25,976 --> 00:46:30,271
One day he told me that people
can't live only for themselves.

828
00:46:31,024 --> 00:46:35,188
He said he was trying to do something
that would be good for everybody.

829
00:46:36,863 --> 00:46:40,280
<i>I know that is what</i>
he is doing now.

830
00:46:41,118 --> 00:46:44,783
<i>He is doing something for</i>
<i>everybody, to give them a better life.</i>

831
00:46:45,998 --> 00:46:48,490
<i>That means he is doing something</i>
<i>for me, too.</i>

832
00:46:49,460 --> 00:46:51,619
So even though he is far away,

833
00:46:52,380 --> 00:46:54,753
he is thinking about me
and I am with him.

834
00:46:56,760 --> 00:46:58,420
That is why I'm not sad.

835
00:46:58,804 --> 00:47:01,093
That is why I'm so proud of my Dad.

836
00:47:01,307 --> 00:47:02,552
I love him so much.'

837
00:47:04,227 --> 00:47:05,057
Kay.

838
00:47:07,647 --> 00:47:08,263
What is it?

839
00:47:10,400 --> 00:47:11,729
There's something I...

840
00:47:12,778 --> 00:47:13,857
I wanna say.

841
00:47:16,490 --> 00:47:17,355
<i>Bru?</i>

842
00:47:18,742 --> 00:47:19,738
<i>What is it?</i>

843
00:47:21,871 --> 00:47:23,151
Not until I tell you.

844
00:47:23,915 --> 00:47:26,916
I know this hasn't been easy
for you and the kids.

845
00:47:30,046 --> 00:47:31,541
I want you to know

846
00:47:32,841 --> 00:47:33,920
I love you.

847
00:47:34,635 --> 00:47:38,639
<i>Tell Charles thanks for</i>
<i>the composition, please.</i>

848
00:47:38,676 --> 00:47:39,505
I will.

849
00:47:39,891 --> 00:47:41,385
Tell him when I get back,

850
00:47:44,562 --> 00:47:46,804
I'm gonna take him to Yosemite again,

851
00:47:48,400 --> 00:47:49,645
like last summer.

852
00:47:53,030 --> 00:47:53,812
I will.

853
00:47:54,198 --> 00:47:56,025
<i>And I want you to know</i>
<i>that I love you.</i>

854
00:47:57,326 --> 00:47:58,441
<i>Very much.</i>

855
00:48:02,165 --> 00:48:03,493
Time's up, gentlemen.

856
00:48:04,084 --> 00:48:05,329
<i>Roger, Houston.</i>

857
00:48:05,502 --> 00:48:07,910
The next time we see you,
you'll be on the way home.

858
00:48:08,088 --> 00:48:10,460
<i>- Roger.</i>
- Well done, Capricorn.

859
00:48:44,127 --> 00:48:44,993
Yes?

860
00:48:45,796 --> 00:48:48,038
Is Whitter in?
Tell him it's Caulfield.

861
00:48:48,257 --> 00:48:50,546
- Who?
- Whitter. Elliot Whitter.

862
00:48:51,761 --> 00:48:53,492
There's no one here by that name.

863
00:48:53,528 --> 00:48:55,186
You must have the wrong apartment.

864
00:48:55,223 --> 00:48:57,548
Well, this is apartment 228,
isn't it?

865
00:48:57,851 --> 00:49:00,896
Yeah. Oh, you probably have
the wrong building.

866
00:49:00,932 --> 00:49:02,653
You know, they are all sorta look alike.

867
00:49:02,689 --> 00:49:06,308
Yeah, that's right.
This is 4311 Claridge, isn't it?

868
00:49:06,777 --> 00:49:07,909
Yeah, it is.

869
00:49:07,945 --> 00:49:11,943
Elliot Whitter lives at 4311 Claridge,
in apartment 228.

870
00:49:12,992 --> 00:49:14,024
Is this a joke?

871
00:49:14,703 --> 00:49:16,418
Look, I've been here a million times.

872
00:49:16,454 --> 00:49:18,946
Elliot's a friend of mine and
he lives in this apartment!

873
00:49:19,333 --> 00:49:22,417
Look, Mister..., whoever you are.
I'm cleaning an oven.

874
00:49:22,628 --> 00:49:25,831
It's my oven. It's in my kitchen.
In my apartment.

875
00:49:26,007 --> 00:49:28,014
If you don't mind,
I'd like to get back to it.

876
00:49:28,050 --> 00:49:31,679
Wait a minute! Just wait! Look, I'm not
a crazy person and I'm not a mugger!

877
00:49:31,716 --> 00:49:34,659
I'm looking for my friend and he lives
in this apartment! I swear it!

878
00:49:34,695 --> 00:49:37,603
Would you get your foot out of my door
or I'm gonna call the police!

879
00:49:37,639 --> 00:49:39,318
Now I don't think this is
funny any more!

880
00:49:39,354 --> 00:49:42,356
Wait. I can prove I've been here before.
I know this apartment.

881
00:50:15,853 --> 00:50:18,770
Now, will you get outta here,
or do I have to call the police?

882
