01:32:14,230 --> 01:32:16,691
I cannot go to Galveston right now.

1388
01:32:16,728 --> 01:32:17,806
I don't think I heard you.

1389
01:32:18,485 --> 01:32:19,399
Look,

1390
01:32:19,695 --> 01:32:22,787
when a reporter tells
his Assignment Editor

1391
01:32:22,823 --> 01:32:26,442
that he thinks he may be onto
something that could be really big,

1392
01:32:26,661 --> 01:32:28,955
the Assignment Editor's suppose
to say,

1393
01:32:28,991 --> 01:32:30,545
'You got forty-eight hours, kid,

1394
01:32:30,582 --> 01:32:32,417
and you better come up
with something good

1395
01:32:32,454 --> 01:32:33,632
or it's gonna be your neck.'

1396
01:32:33,668 --> 01:32:36,129
That's what he's supposed to say!
I saw it in a movie!

1397
01:32:36,166 --> 01:32:37,690
Get your ass on that plane!

1398
01:32:37,727 --> 01:32:39,180
I can't! I have to follow this!

1399
01:32:39,216 --> 01:32:41,907
And you can't tell me what this
earth-shattering story is?

1400
01:32:41,943 --> 01:32:44,597
It sounds too crazy.
If I told you, I'd be in more trouble.

1401
01:32:44,633 --> 01:32:47,559
You're not crazy! I'm crazy!
I'm crazy for listening!

1402
01:32:47,595 --> 01:32:49,983
And I'm crazy for saying what
I'm about to say!

1403
01:32:50,020 --> 01:32:52,486
I'll give you twenty-four hours
come up with something!

1404
01:32:52,522 --> 01:32:55,808
Not forty-eight! I saw the movie, too,
and it was twenty-four!

1405
01:34:05,852 --> 01:34:06,848
Freeze!

1406
01:34:07,646 --> 01:34:09,857
- I'm not moving an inch.
- Robert Caulfield?

1407
01:34:09,893 --> 01:34:11,939
- Yeah, who the hell are you?
- Federal Agents.

1408
01:34:11,976 --> 01:34:13,950
We have a warrant to search
your apartment.

1409
01:34:13,986 --> 01:34:17,153
- You have a warrant? What for?
- Just don't move.

1410
01:34:17,448 --> 01:34:19,701
I promise. Just tell me
what this is all about.

1411
01:34:19,737 --> 01:34:21,112
<i>Hey, come here! Look at this!</i>

1412
01:34:21,286 --> 01:34:23,362
Could you come with me,
please, Mr. Caulfield?

1413
01:34:52,946 --> 01:34:54,773
Mr. Caulfield, I'm sorry.

1414
01:34:55,282 --> 01:34:58,033
However, you're under arrest
for possession of cocaine.

1415
01:34:58,368 --> 01:34:59,566
I don't believe it.

1416
01:35:00,496 --> 01:35:03,117
I don't believe it. You guys put it there,
you know you did.

1417
01:35:03,624 --> 01:35:05,332
You have the right to remain silent.

1418
01:35:08,379 --> 01:35:11,633
- You have the right to an attorney.
- I don't believe it. You put it there.

1419
01:35:11,669 --> 01:35:14,338
Anything you say may be held
against you in a court of law.

1420
01:35:14,886 --> 01:35:17,757
You're part of all this. You mothers.

1421
01:35:19,016 --> 01:35:20,214
Ow, that hurts!

1422
01:35:20,476 --> 01:35:22,149
You don't have to put
handcuffs on me!

1423
01:35:22,186 --> 01:35:24,986
Please, Mr. Caulfield, these are
serious charges against you.

1424
01:35:25,022 --> 01:35:28,189
- Don't add to them by resisting arrest.
- I don't bel...! That hurts!

1425
01:35:29,027 --> 01:35:30,521
I don't believe this.

1426
01:35:39,497 --> 01:35:42,367
Well, hello there, Caulfield!
So nice to see you!

1427
01:35:42,959 --> 01:35:46,328
It's at this point that Alan Hale says
to Richard Conte...

1428
01:35:46,921 --> 01:35:49,236
- Jimmy Stewart.
- Yeah, Jimmy Stewart, thank you.

1429
01:35:49,273 --> 01:35:51,551
Look, Scoop, I can't keep bailing you
out of trouble.

1430
01:35:51,588 --> 01:35:52,933
The front office is on my neck.

1431
01:35:52,970 --> 01:35:56,181
I don't know how much longer
I can keep them off, right?

1432
01:35:56,218 --> 01:35:57,146
- Right.
- Wrong!

1433
01:35:57,183 --> 01:35:59,894
I got you out of there so as not to
embarrass the Network.

1434
01:35:59,930 --> 01:36:02,605
I mean, you are a schmuck!
I can't trust you to cover a fire!

1435
01:36:02,642 --> 01:36:04,604
You'll probably fall down
and get burned!

1436
01:36:04,641 --> 01:36:06,568
You probably would be the cause of it!

1437
01:36:06,604 --> 01:36:08,691
A company car? You are fired!

1438
01:36:08,820 --> 01:36:12,032
I love that so much!
I'm gonna say it again!

1439
01:36:12,069 --> 01:36:15,244
You're fired! You're through!
Oh, I love it!

1440
01:36:15,280 --> 01:36:17,126
It's not what it looks like, really.

1441
01:36:17,163 --> 01:36:19,452
'Frankly, Scarlet, I don't give a damn!'

1442
01:36:22,168 --> 01:36:25,422
I told you. You tell me about the lonely
plight of a dedicated journalist.

1443
01:36:25,458 --> 01:36:26,511
I tell you to stuff it.

1444
01:36:26,548 --> 01:36:28,467
You tell me about a meaningful
relationship.

1445
01:36:28,503 --> 01:36:29,723
I tell you to stuff it.

1446
01:36:29,760 --> 01:36:31,971
You tell me you're in trouble,
you're out on bail,

1447
01:36:32,007 --> 01:36:34,181
you just got fired,
I tell you I'll be right over.

1448
01:36:34,218 --> 01:36:35,938
- My head hurts.
- You look awful.

1449
01:36:35,975 --> 01:36:37,977
- Thank you, very much.
- You're quite welcome.

1450
01:36:38,014 --> 01:36:39,353
Did you find out what I asked?

1451
01:36:39,646 --> 01:36:42,899
One o'clock in the morning
I get a call from an unemployed junkie

1452
01:36:42,936 --> 01:36:46,153
to find out all the military installations
in a 300 miles radius

1453
01:36:46,189 --> 01:36:47,159
around Houston, Texas.

1454
01:36:47,196 --> 01:36:49,885
You certainly have a way with words.
Did you find out?

1455
01:36:49,921 --> 01:36:52,574
Yes, and it wasn't easy.
It took exhaustive research.

1456
01:36:52,785 --> 01:36:54,459
Well, I'm proud of you.
How many?

1457
01:36:54,495 --> 01:36:58,166
One. White Bluff. It's a S AC base.
My father used to be stationed there.

1458
01:36:58,202 --> 01:36:59,874
That's exhaustive research?

1459
01:36:59,959 --> 01:37:03,130
At one o'clock in the morning,
you call your father, that's exhaustive.

1460
01:37:03,166 --> 01:37:05,382
- White Bluff... That's too big.
- Too big for what?

1461
01:37:05,419 --> 01:37:07,593
- Too big for what I want.
- What do you want?

1462
01:37:07,629 --> 01:37:09,058
I'm thinking of enlisting.

1463
01:37:09,094 --> 01:37:11,889
- They'll never take you.
- That's why I'm thinking of enlisting.

1464
01:37:11,926 --> 01:37:14,272
- You're on a story, aren't you?
- I was fired!

1465
01:37:14,308 --> 01:37:17,103
You're on a story and I'm helping you.
This can't be happening.

1466
01:37:17,140 --> 01:37:18,360
I really appreciate that.

1467
01:37:18,396 --> 01:37:21,024
The only reason I'm doing it,
considering your track record,

1468
01:37:21,061 --> 01:37:23,819
whatever story you're on
will turn out to be garbage.

1469
01:37:23,855 --> 01:37:25,479
You shouldn't mince words.

1470
01:37:32,578 --> 01:37:34,785
I'll fix you some coffee.
Then you can jump me.

1471
01:37:35,123 --> 01:37:37,163
There's no other one besides
White Bluff?

1472
01:37:37,417 --> 01:37:38,331
No.

1473
01:37:38,794 --> 01:37:41,510
Except one abandoned base
they used for training

1474
01:37:41,547 --> 01:37:44,764
during World War II, Jackson.
There's nothing there now.

1475
01:37:44,800 --> 01:37:47,718
- Don't you want to jump me?
- Of course I do. Where's Jackson?

1476
01:37:49,430 --> 01:37:53,049
About 300 miles directly West.
I think I'm gonna get angry with you.

1477
01:37:53,727 --> 01:37:56,432
- Do you have any money on you?
- Do you want me to pay you?

1478
01:37:56,855 --> 01:37:57,861
How much?

1479
01:37:57,898 --> 01:38:00,859
About 100. Why don't I just leave it
on the dresser in the morning?

1480
01:38:00,896 --> 01:38:01,855
Give it to me now.

1481
01:38:02,236 --> 01:38:04,363
In advance?
That's the height of conceit!

1482
01:38:04,400 --> 01:38:06,403
Please, and your car keys.

1483
01:38:10,161 --> 01:38:11,953
You're really being terrific, why?

1484
01:38:13,415 --> 01:38:15,703
You're not as obnoxious
when you are helpless.

1485
01:38:15,739 --> 01:38:17,992
- Thank you very much.
- You're quite welcome.

1486
01:38:19,880 --> 01:38:22,263
Also, Liz Haller said you were super.

1487
01:38:22,299 --> 01:38:25,336
Well, when I get back,
we'll jump each other.

1488
01:38:25,553 --> 01:38:26,502
Maybe.

1489
01:38:28,598 --> 01:38:29,796
I'll get arrested again.

1490
01:38:31,059 --> 01:38:32,055
It's a deal.

1491
01:45:15,042 --> 01:45:16,074
Mornin'.

1492
01:45:18,671 --> 01:45:20,711
- Mornin'.
- You in charge here?

1493
01:45:22,300 --> 01:45:23,927
- You see that sign there?
- Yes.

1494
01:45:23,964 --> 01:45:24,933
Well, read it.

1495
01:45:24,970 --> 01:45:26,085
- I did.
- Out loud!

1496
01:45:26,638 --> 01:45:28,927
'A and A Crop Dusting Service'.

1497
01:45:29,266 --> 01:45:30,891
You wanna know who I am?

1498
01:45:31,394 --> 01:45:33,025
I'll bet you're one of the 'A's.

1499
01:45:33,062 --> 01:45:36,065
Well, which one? I'll bet you can't
answer that question, smart-ass!

1500
01:45:36,102 --> 01:45:37,310
- The first one.
- Wrong!

1501
01:45:37,734 --> 01:45:40,307
- Can I have one more guess?
- You got it.

1502
01:45:40,612 --> 01:45:41,857
The second one.

1503
01:45:42,489 --> 01:45:46,569
Wrong. I'm both of 'em!
'A' and 'A'. My name is Albain.

1504
01:45:46,827 --> 01:45:51,332
I got a son. The other 'A' was for him,
but he don't like to fly and is a lawyer.

1505
01:45:51,368 --> 01:45:53,256
He's a pervert, so I took the 'A'
away.

1506
01:45:53,292 --> 01:45:55,997
Wanna speak to somebody in charge?
You're speakin' to both o' them.

1507
01:45:56,254 --> 01:45:59,028
- My name is Caulfield.
- Hey, I can't help that.

1508
01:45:59,064 --> 01:46:01,802
Mr. Albain, how much do you charge
to dust a field?

1509
01:46:01,838 --> 01:46:04,293
- 25 dollars.
- I'd like to hire your plane.

1510
01:46:04,638 --> 01:46:07,592
- That'll be 100 dollars.
- You said you charged 25.

1511
01:46:07,975 --> 01:46:11,771
25 dollars t' dust a field, but you ain't
got no field because you ain't a farmer,

1512
01:46:11,807 --> 01:46:14,441
which means you ain't poor
and I think you're a pervert!

1513
01:46:15,609 --> 01:46:16,990
Okay, 100.

1514
01:46:17,027 --> 01:46:18,951
- 125.
- What?

1515
01:46:18,987 --> 01:46:21,407
Because you said 'yes' to 100
too quick,

1516
01:46:21,443 --> 01:46:23,316
which means you can afford 125!

1517
01:46:30,583 --> 01:46:32,007
Where do you wanna go,
smart-ass?

1518
01:46:32,043 --> 01:46:34,212
I'm not sure. I'm looking for someone
who's lost.

1519
01:46:34,249 --> 01:46:35,327
It's your money.

1520
01:48:08,524 --> 01:48:11,652
Put your Goddamn head down
so I can see!

1521
01:48:11,689 --> 01:48:13,526
Why didn't you sit in front?

1522
01:48:14,196 --> 01:48:16,106
- You know how to fly?
- No!

1523
01:48:16,657 --> 01:48:18,707
Then I gotta sit in back

1524
01:48:18,743 --> 01:48:22,278
and you gotta put your Goddamn
head down, smart-ass!

1525
01:49:01,790 --> 01:49:04,168
Now, what the hell is your friend doin'
out here?

1526
01:49:04,204 --> 01:49:05,283
He's lost!

1527
01:49:06,337 --> 01:49:08,626
- He rob a bank or somethin'?
- No!

1528
01:49:09,715 --> 01:49:11,839
- Well, I get a third!
- What?

1529
01:49:12,135 --> 01:49:14,596
We find him, I get a third of the loot!

1530
01:49:14,632 --> 01:49:16,672
Now, keep your Goddamn head down!

1531
01:50:07,988 --> 01:50:10,365
You think we should go
in another direction?

1532
01:50:10,402 --> 01:50:11,705
- Hey!
- What?

1533
01:50:11,742 --> 01:50:13,485
- Over there!
- Where?

1534
01:50:13,827 --> 01:50:15,156
Helicopters!

1535
01:50:15,245 --> 01:50:17,404
I seen them fly around here
last couple of days!

1536
01:50:17,581 --> 01:50:19,870
- Let's follow 'em!
- I would if I could see 'em!

1537
01:51:24,821 --> 01:51:26,648
They're goin' down over there!

1538
01:51:55,772 --> 01:51:57,397
He must be in there!

1539
01:51:57,983 --> 01:51:59,145
Let's go down.

1540
01:52:00,319 --> 01:52:02,062
They got guns, Sonny!

1541
01:52:02,780 --> 01:52:05,105
You said you wanted a third of the loot!

1542
01:52:05,950 --> 01:52:08,358
- Half!
- Okay, half!

1543
01:55:10,318 --> 01:55:12,358
Keep your Goddamn head down!

1544
01:57:17,499 --> 01:57:20,749
Pull that lever down by your feet
when I tell you, Sonny!

1545
01:57:30,721 --> 01:57:31,836
Now!

1546
01:58:04,175 --> 01:58:05,373
Perverts!

1547
01:58:06,302 --> 01:58:07,880
Remember, I get half!

1548
01:58:15,938 --> 01:58:17,313
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

1549
01:58:17,397 --> 01:58:18,643
<i>Mrs. Brubaker</i>

1550
01:58:18,983 --> 01:58:21,308
<i>Mrs. Willis, Mrs. Walker,</i>

1551
01:58:22,069 --> 01:58:23,564
<i>my fellow Americans.</i>

1552
01:58:24,363 --> 01:58:27,780
<i>I come here today to talk of</i>
<i>unfinished hopes</i>

1553
01:58:28,410 --> 01:58:30,402
<i>and of unfulfilled dreams.</i>

1554
01:58:30,954 --> 01:58:34,619
<i>Charles Brubaker, Peter Willis</i>
<i>and John Walker</i>

1555
01:58:35,125 --> 01:58:39,289
<i>left this Earth for their dream</i>
<i>a little more than eight months ago.</i>

1556
01:58:39,547 --> 01:58:41,836
<i>They were never able</i>
<i>to return to us.</i>

1557
01:58:42,800 --> 01:58:45,885
Their dream was able to grow
and flourish

1558
01:58:46,387 --> 01:58:49,724
because of the support of millions
of citizens

1559
01:58:49,761 --> 01:58:50,839
all across America

1560
01:58:51,685 --> 01:58:55,137
at a time when cynicism was
a national epidemic,

1561
01:58:56,190 --> 01:58:59,191
they gave us something
to take pride in.

1562
01:59:00,319 --> 01:59:03,902
It is a dream that
should not be allowed to die.

1563
01:59:05,575 --> 01:59:08,991
A nation is built on the spirit
of its people.

1564
01:59:10,163 --> 01:59:12,322
The test of the greatness
of any nation

1565
01:59:12,666 --> 01:59:15,620
is how that nation pulls together
in a time of crisis.

1566
01:59:16,796 --> 01:59:19,420
The only limits on what
we can achieve

1567
01:59:19,457 --> 01:59:22,045
are the limits we place on our hopes.

1568
01:59:22,719 --> 01:59:28,010
These three men reminded us
of the limitlessness of our hopes.

1569
01:59:29,017 --> 01:59:32,138
There was a moment
in these past few days

1570
01:59:32,605 --> 01:59:35,440
when we were all one people.

1571
01:59:35,900 --> 01:59:38,023
We were all hoping,

1572
01:59:38,570 --> 01:59:40,609
we were all a little bit taller,

1573
01:59:41,197 --> 01:59:42,740
a little bit prouder.

1574
01:59:43,158 --> 01:59:46,990
We were all feeling the same fears
and the same exhilaration.

1575
01:59:47,454 --> 01:59:49,962
These three men brought us together.

1576
01:59:49,999 --> 01:59:54,211
We knew together that
there are no goals we cannot reach

1577
01:59:54,670 --> 01:59:57,340
if just reach for them together.

1578
01:59:58,508 --> 02:00:00,797
There is no adequate way

1579
02:00:01,219 --> 02:00:04,885
in which we can express our gratitude
to the men themselves

1580
02:00:05,724 --> 02:00:08,429
because they are no longer among us.

1581
02:00:09,270 --> 02:00:12,437
However,
we can serve their memory,

1582
02:00:12,648 --> 02:00:14,143
what they stood for...